{{Orphan|date=September 2016}}
'''Chaotic rotation''' involves the irregular and unpredictable [[rotation]] of an astronomical body. Unlike [[Earth's rotation]], a chaotic rotation may not have a fixed axis or period. Because of the [[conservation of angular momentum]], chaotic rotation is not seen in objects that are [[spherically symmetric]] or well isolated from gravitational interaction, but is the result of the interactions within a system of orbiting bodies, similar to those associated with [[orbital resonance]].
Examples of chaotic rotation include [[Hyperion (moon)|Hyperion]],<ref> {{cite journal |first1 = J. | last1 = Wisdom | first2 = S. J. | last2 = Peale | first3 = F. | last3 = Mignard |date=1984 |title=The chaotic rotation of Hyperion |journal=[[Icarus (journal)|Icarus]] |volume=58 |issue= 2|pages=137–152 |bibcode=1984Icar...58..137W |doi=10.1016/0019-1035(84)90032-0 }}</ref> a moon of [[Saturn]], which rotates so unpredictably that the [[Cassini probe]] could not be reliably scheduled to pass by unexplored regions,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2015/05/30/nasa_cassini_final_hyperion_saturn_flyby/ |title=It's not over 'til Saturn's spongy moon sings: Cassini probe set for final Hyperion fly-by |publisher=[[The Register]] |date=2015-05-30 |author=Kelly Fiveash}}</ref> and [[moons of Pluto|Pluto's]] [[Nix (moon)|Nix]], [[Hydra (moon)|Hydra]], and possibly [[Styx (moon)|Styx]] and [[Kerberos (moon)|Kerberos]], and also [[moons of Neptune|Neptune's]] [[Nereid (moon)|Nereid]].<ref>{{cite journal | bibcode = 2014DDA....4530402S | title=Chaotic Rotation of Nix and Hydra | volume=45 | year=2014 | authors=Showalter, Mark R.}}</ref> According to Mark R. Showalter, author of a recent study,<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v522/n7554/full/nature14469.html |title=Resonant interactions and chaotic rotation of Pluto’s small moons |author=M. R. Showalter, D. P. Hamilton |journal=Nature |volume=522 |pages=45–49 |doi=10.1038/nature14469 |bibcode = 2015Natur.522...45S |pmid=26040889|date=Jun 2015}}</ref> "Nix can flip its entire pole. It could actually be possible to spend a day on Nix in which the sun rises in the east and sets in the north. It is almost random-looking in the way it rotates."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/04/science/space/pluto-moons-orbits-described-in-nature-article.html |title=Astronomers Describe Chaotic Dance of Pluto’s Moons |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=2015-06-03 |author=Kenneth Chang}}</ref> Another example is that of [[Galaxy|galaxies]]; from careful observation by the [[Keck telescope|Keck]] and [[Hubble Space Telescope|Hubble]] telescopes of hundreds of galaxies, a trend was discovered that suggests galaxies such as our own [[Milky Way]] used to have a very chaotic rotation, with [[Planet|planetary bodies]] and stars rotating randomly. New evidence<ref>NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}</ref> suggests that our galaxy and other have settled into an orderly, disk-like rotation over the past 8 billion years{{Failed verification|date=May 2017}} and that other galaxies are slowly following suit over time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/topics/universe/features/galaxy-evol.html |title=NASA – Astronomers Uncover A Surprising Trend in Galaxy Evolution |website=www.nasa.gov |language=en |access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref>
